TECHNOLOGY GROUND RULES — READ CAREFULLY:
Neural interfaces are the core technology. By 2093, neural implants have evolved from today's Neuralink into something mature and ubiquitous. Here's the baseline:

The neural interface replaces the smartphone. Everyone has some form of brain-computer interface. At the fierro level, it's a basic implant — probably evolved from the kind of thing Neuralink is doing today — that provides an AR overlay directly in your vision, audio in your hearing, sub-vocal communication (think commands without speaking out loud), and connection to your walled garden. At the vitral level, it's a fully biological neural mesh that's indistinguishable from natural brain function.
The AR overlay is how people see the digital world. Not through contacts, not through glasses — through the implant itself projecting onto the visual cortex. You SEE your messages, your maps, your notifications, your entertainment, overlaid on the physical world. The quality of this overlay varies by tier — fierro users get a grainy, laggy, ad-riddled overlay; vitral users get seamless, perfect integration where digital and physical are indistinguishable.
Think about what this REPLACES and what NEW problems it creates. No phones, no screens needed (though external screens still exist as shared/public displays). Communication is thought-to-thought at the high end, sub-vocal at the low end. But: Neural Dissonance from garden-crossing, hacking/intrusion risks, corporate surveillance through your own implant, addiction to overlay stimulation, the class gap between someone with a grainy fierro interface and someone with a seamless vitral one.
Personal Switch Hubs. The rich can afford personal switch hub hardware — a portable or home device that lets them transition between walled gardens smoothly, avoiding Neural Dissonance. For everyone else, you physically go to a public Switch Hub (think of an internet café meets a toll booth meets a social club) or you suffer through rough transitions.
Build from today's tech trajectory. Neuralink → mature neural interfaces. AirPods/bone conduction → integrated neural audio. Apple Vision Pro/AR glasses → direct cortical AR overlay. Smartphones → obsolete, replaced by the implant. Smart home → neurally controlled. Cars → autonomous but you can neurally interface with your vehicle. Crypto/digital wallets → neural-integrated payment.
Bodies are augmented, not replaced. This isn't full-cyborg territory. Implants are small, biological where possible, integrated. Think medical devices that also happen to give you superpowers, not robot arms (though prosthetics exist). Nanotech in the bloodstream. Subdermal sensors. Enhanced senses. The body is UPGRADED, not swapped out.
Braindance equivalent. Full sensory recordings exist — someone records an experience (sight, sound, touch, taste, smell, emotion) through their neural interface and others can play it back, experiencing exactly what that person experienced. This is a huge entertainment industry AND a huge black market (illegal recordings, stolen experiences, celebrity experience leaks). What's the Santiago-specific name and culture around this?
VR vs AR. AR overlay is daily life (you see digital information over the real world). Full VR immersion requires hardware — SR Pods for full-body, or lighter rigs like headsets/chairs for shorter sessions. KyotoKyo dominates the VR/immersion market with their Aether Casket line.

